[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThat said, two WARNINGs need attention before this goes to readers, plus seven NOTEs. The first WARNING is that Pass 3's API call is documented as "last-name + primary taxonomy + state" but the code passes [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140m"taxonomy_description": ""[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m as the parameter value rather than the internal record's NUCC code or its description; the gating condition ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140minternal_record["primary_taxonomy"] != "unknown_taxonomy"[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m) checks that there IS a taxonomy on the internal side, but the value is never threaded through to the API call, so Pass 3 degrades to a [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mlast_name + state + enumeration_type[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m query that is structurally identical to Pass 2. A reader copying the example into production would carry forward an incorrect understanding of what Pass 3 does and would believe the API was filtering by taxonomy at the index level when it isn't. The second WARNING is that [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mre_verify_npi[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m emits only two of the three drift events the pseudocode promises: [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mnpi_deactivated[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mpractice_address_changed[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m are emitted, but [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mtaxonomy_changed[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m is computed (the drift dictionary carries [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mtaxonomy_changed: True/False[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m) and then silently dropped. The recipe text emphasizes taxonomy drift as a real concern (a provider who newly attests a subspecialty is a directory-and-network-adequacy event), and the pseudocode block in Step 6 explicitly lists the three events; a reader who diff'd the pseudocode against the Python would see the gap.[K
